# Code Organization â€” HTML Comments & TS Regions

When generating or editing Angular component `.html` and `.ts` files, structure code so sections are easy to scan. Use **HTML comments** for template sections and **`//#region` / `//#endregion`** for TypeScript logic groups.

## TypeScript (`.ts`)

Group related code by **topic / responsibility**. Use collapsible region tags (IDE-friendly) with clear names.

### Standard regions (use what applies; skip empty sections)

| Region | Contents |
| --- | --- |
| `//#region Types` | Local types, interfaces, type aliases |
| `//#region Dependencies` | `inject()` calls, `viewChild` / `viewChildren` |
| `//#region State` | `signal()`, `model()`, writable state |
| `//#region Derived state` | `computed()` |
| `//#region Lifecycle` | `constructor`, lifecycle hooks, `afterNextRender` |
| `//#region Event handlers` | User interaction handlers (`onClick`, `onSubmit`, â€¦) |
| `//#region Navigation` | Tab/step routing, view switching |
| `//#region Form` | Form state, validation, submit logic |
| `//#region API` | HTTP calls, data loading, side effects |
| `//#region Helpers` | Pure utility functions private to the component |

### Rules

- One blank line before each `//#region` and after each `//#endregion`.
- Region names: **PascalCase**, short and descriptive (e.g. `//#region File upload`, `//#region Tab navigation`).
- Do **not** wrap single one-liners in their own region â€” merge small related items.
- Do **not** add regions inside `@Component({ ... })` metadata â€” only around class body members.
- Imports stay **outside** regions at the top of the file (no region around imports unless the file is very large).

### Example

```typescript
import { Component, computed, inject, signal } from '@angular/core';

type ViewMode = 'list' | 'detail';

@Component({ /* ... */ })
export class MyPage {
  //#region Dependencies
  private readonly api = inject(MyApiService);
  //#endregion

  //#region State
  protected readonly viewMode = signal<ViewMode>('list');
  protected readonly items = signal<Item[]>([]);
  //#endregion

  //#region Derived state
  protected readonly isEmpty = computed(() => this.items().length === 0);
  //#endregion

  //#region Event handlers
  protected onItemSelect(item: Item): void {
    this.viewMode.set('detail');
  }
  //#endregion
}
```

## HTML templates (`.html`)

Add **section comments** above major blocks so the template reads top-to-bottom like a page outline.

### What to comment

- Page shell (wrapper, layout)
- Header / footer / toolbar
- Main content areas
- Wizard steps, tabs, or conditional views (`@if` branches)
- Repeated card/list sections
- Sticky action bars (submit, navigation buttons)
- Status screens (loading, success, error)

### Comment format

```html
<!-- Section name -->
...markup...

<!-- / Section name -->
```

- Use a short **title case** label (e.g. `<!-- Header -->`, `<!-- Step 2: Documents -->`, `<!-- Submit actions -->`).
- Close optional for top-level sections; use `<!-- / Section name -->` when nesting is deep or sections are long.
- Place the opening comment on its own line **immediately above** the element it describes.
- Do **not** comment every `<div>` â€” only meaningful UI sections.
- Do **not** restate obvious markup (`<!-- div -->`). Describe **purpose**, not tag names.

### Example

```html
<!-- Page shell -->
<div class="flex min-h-dvh flex-col">
  <!-- Header -->
  <header>...</header>

  @if (view() === 'form') {
    <!-- Wizard tabs -->
    <ax-tabs>...</ax-tabs>

    <!-- Step 1: Personal info -->
  <ax-form>...</ax-form>
  }

  @if (view() === 'success') {
    <!-- Success state -->
    <section>...</section>
  }

  <!-- Footer actions -->
  <footer>...</footer>
</div>
<!-- / Page shell -->
```

## When generating new components or pages

1. Plan sections first (header, form, actions, states).
2. Write the HTML skeleton with section comments.
3. Implement the `.ts` file with matching region names where helpful (e.g. `//#region Form` aligns with `<!-- Personal info form -->`).
4. Keep region/comment names **consistent** between `.ts` and `.html` when they represent the same feature.

